#first we figure out how to do the poisson regression, and then recall that the coefficients, if not exponentiated, is the difference in log mean per unit difference of our parameter. However, when exponentiated, it is the ratio between mean number of the response per unit difference of our variable.
poisRes= glm(count1 ~ dose +sex +age +count0, family="poisson", data=cellData)
psum = summary(poisRes)
print(psum)

Now interpreting the coefficients, holding everything else constant, the baseline for factor(0) is 91 ratio of mean post cell count. Relative to it, the exponentiated coefficients for factor(dose) 10 and 100 have a multplicative factor compared to factor(0) of 0.1 and 14.57. However, factor(dose) 10 doesnt appear to be significant in this model.

a)Looking at the results of our logistic regression model, we see that PDALL and AGE are significant.

b)Interpreting the coefficients for the model, we see for the logistic regression, the odds of a patient having a tooth extracted increases by 4.27 percent per unit increase in PDALL assuming all else held constant. the exponetiated coefficient indicates an increase in the odds of a patient having a tooth extracted by 1.03 percent per unit increase in age assuming all else held constant.

c)Looking at the results of the poisson regression, we can see that only PDALL is significant in this model.

  1. Finally for the poisson model, the exponentiated coefficient of 2.5 for PDALL indicates an increase in the rate ratio by a factor of that 2.5 per unit increase in the PDALL term assuming all other terms held constant. Note the baseline ratio of 0.0022. I do not bother interpreting the other parameters as they are not signficant.

  2. Overall, the models give similar results. They both indicate a positive relationship between the odds of a patient having a tooth extracted and the PDALL term. However, they disagree on the significance of the age relationship, but agree on its sign.

Problem 4, bonus

Lets tackle this proof through simulation.

minXs = rep(10,25)
maxXs = rep(40,25)
allData = c(minXs,maxXs)
meanX = mean(allData)
print(meanX)
## [1] 25
print(sum((allData-meanX)**2))
## [1] 11250

Now, we know that our assumptions of linearity, constant variance, and indepndence are met.

We further understand that the formula for \(SE(\hat{\beta}) = \frac{\hat{\sigma}}{\sqrt{\sum^{n=50}_{i=1}(X_i-\bar{X})^2}}\)

Knowing this, along with out assumptions, we can see that our \(\hat{\sigma}\) and \(n\) are constant. Thus, the only thing that can change in our calculation is the value of \(\sqrt{\sum^{n=50}_{i=1}(X_i-\bar{X})^2}\). Further, given the range \(10 \le X_i \le 40\), we must ensure our values satisfy this requirement.

We can see inuitively, that we must maximize that square root of a sum to maximize the denominator and ultimatley minimize the SE.

Thus, lets examine what happens to the sum of squared differences (ignoring the square root as it is meaningless to our goal) when we shift some values around.

newData = allData
newData[50] = 39
newMean = mean(newData)
print(newMean)
## [1] 24.98
print(sum((newData-newMean)**2))
## [1] 11220.98

We can see that lowering one of our Xs at 40 resulted in a net decrease in sum of squared differences. This trend holds due to the negative derivative found when taking the first derivative of our \(SE\) with respect to our \(X_i\).

The same holds for increasing our Xs at 10, due to the symmetric property of this relationship.

If we shift all data down, our results should reflect, inuitively, another overal decrease.

minXs = rep(10,25)
maxXs = rep(39,25)
allData = c(minXs,maxXs)
meanX = mean(allData)
print(meanX)
## [1] 24.5
print(sum((allData-meanX)**2))
## [1] 10512.5

looking at all results, we can see that negative relationship we refferred to.

startMax = 40
results = numeric()
vals = numeric()
counter = 1
while(startMax>=10)
{
  minXs = rep(10,25)
  maxXs = rep(startMax,25)
  allData = c(minXs,maxXs)
  meanX = mean(allData)
  results[counter] = sum((allData-meanX)**2)
  vals[counter] = startMax
  counter = counter +1
  startMax= startMax-1
}
plot(x=vals,y=results)

This would normally continue on indefinetly if there were no bounds to either end of our range.
